  footnotes: []
english:
  title: 'Night of the Eighteenth Day of the Sixth Month: Lodging at Heungcheon Temple with Taekji and Seonji'
  author: Park Eun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    By the twin pines where sacred relics rest,
    Clouds and moon make the night clear and cool.
    Three friends meeting by chance—
    who speaks of ten thousand tasks pressing?
    We shed our robes for comfort alone,
    raise our cups until madness comes.
    The resident monks must think us strange,
    our lofty talk beyond all measure.

    [The poet notes: That night Taekji chanted these two lines:
    "Ten thousand tasks invade—only one drunkenness remains,
    A hundred years of longing, three companions complete it."]

    Seeking the monks through the ancient temple,
    waiting for moonrise beneath the pine's shadow.
    The night air comes stealing over us,
    clear wind scatters through our open robes.
    All kindred spirits gather here together—
    such days are rare, even since ancient times.
    With hearts fully opened again,
    let no worldly care intrude.

    A knock at the door as night falls urgently—
    a guest arrives in sudden haste,
    bringing Han River rain upon his sleeves,
    South Mountain's wind filling his garments.
    Long we feared this fine gathering lost,
    yet suddenly all of us laugh as one.
    Such pleasures must be fully enjoyed—
    our only fear is the wine cup emptied.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Heungcheon Temple: A major Buddhist temple in ancient Korea, likely located near Seoul'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Han River and South Mountain: Geographic markers evoking the landscape around the capital'
  - key: ''
    value: The embedded couplet attributed to Taekji reflects the poem's central tension between worldly obligations and the pursuit of friendship and wine
